Prometheus, the Titan, who stole fire from heaven for men, was chained to a rock, and a vulture continually gnawed his lrver. But in the ordinary form of the legend, the rock was in the Caucasus, and Prometheus was set free by Hercules. Horace has this version, however, infr. 18. 35, and Epod. 17. 67.

Pelopis parens. Tantalus, who sor his sins was set in Hades up to the waist in water that always receded from his lips; over his head hung fruit, which the wind swung away as osten as he stretched out to it.

1. 38. Dulci laborum decipitur sono, ‘by the sweet sound is beguiled out of his agonies.'

decipitur, as osten in Horace, agrees with nearest subject, though logically constructed with both. The genitive laborum is a poetic construction imitated from the Greek, where κλέπτεται πόνων might easily stand sor λήθεται πόνων.
